ebates surrounding realism and an original and timely re-imagining of liberal theory for the twenty-first century. This provocative work will be of interest to students and all concerned with the possibility of realising liberalism and its moral aspirations in today’s world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFree enterprise. 0aLiberalism. 0aRealism. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aCoercion.  aConflict.  aLegitimacy.  aLiberalism.  aPluralism.  aPolitics.  aRealism.1 aSleat, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610254640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102546/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles